Part 1: Project Ideas

Initial Project Concepts:

During the brainstorming phase, I considered three different rule-based AI project ideas:

1.  Game Recommendation System

A system that recommends video games based on user preferences such as genre, platform, playstyle, and difficulty level using conditional logic and keyword matching.

2.  Streamer Troubleshooting Assistant

An interactive assistant to help streamers diagnose and resolve common technical issues with OBS, microphones, lag, and streaming platforms using decision-tree style rules.

3.  YouTube SEO Optimizer (Selected Project)

A tool that optimizes YouTube video metadata including titles, tags, and descriptions based on content category and user input using rule-based logic.

Justification for Chosen Project:

I selected the YouTube SEO Optimizer because it directly aligns with my personal interests and current projects. 
I actively manage multiple YouTube Shorts channels (including gaming clips) where effective SEO is crucial for visibility and growth. 
Additionally, I am developing VODForge, an AI-powered clipping and posting service for streamers. 
This tool is highly practical and something I can continue using after the assignment.

Part 2: Rules and Logic

The YouTube SEO Optimizer is a pure rule-based system that applies predefined SEO strategies based on video categories. 
The system uses if-elif-else conditionals, dictionary lookups, and string manipulation.

Core Rules:
•  Category Detection: Matches user input to known categories (gaming, streaming, tech, fitness, general) with fallback logic.
•  Title Optimization: Adds power words if missing, appends category hooks, and enforces ~70 character limit.
•  Tag Generation: Expands base title with category-specific boosters + general high-value tags (max 30 unique tags).
•  Description Starter: Generates intro text, timestamps, CTA, and hashtags.
•  Fallback: Handles empty or unclear inputs gracefully.


