Part 4: Reflection

My rule-based YouTube SEO Optimizer takes a video category and base title as input, then applies a series of heuristics and -
predefined rules to output an optimized title, relevant tags, and a description starter. 
The entire system relies on if-elif conditionals, dictionary lookups for category boosters, and string operations — 
no machine learning is used at all.
I chose this project because it connects directly to my YouTube Shorts work and VODForge development. 
While collaborating with the AI (including GitHub Copilot) to design and code the system, the main challenges were - 
keeping the implementation strictly rule-based while making the outputs actually useful and professional. 
Early versions produced generic results, so I had to iterate multiple times on prompts to refine power-word logic, character limits, category-specific boosters, and output formatting. 
Handling edge cases like empty inputs and unknown categories also required extra refinement.
This assignment gave me a much better understanding of how AI systems worked before machine learning became dominant. 
Rule-based systems are very transparent, easy to debug, and don’t require large datasets, but they can be brittle if the rules don’t cover a particular input. 
Overall, it was a valuable learning experience that reinforced the importance of clear logic and iterative development. 
I’m excited to keep improving this tool for my own content creation workflow.